Threshold

Calculate quantiles according to distance. This is done to select a threshold:

quantiles_d <- quantile(as.vector(ttm_walk$travel_time), probs = c(0, 1/10, 3/10, 5/10, 7/10, 8/10, 9/10))

# dist_threshold <- quantile(as.vector(ttm_walk$travel_time), probs = c(0, 1/10, 3/10, 5/10, 7/10, 8/10, 9/10))[[5]]

# distance threshold has to be less than 30, maximum distance people are willing to go is distance threshold

dist_threshold <- 10

The distance threshold is equivalent to the kernel bandwidth or catchment distance.

dist_threshold
[1] 10

Our calculations assume that 70% of population cells have at least one station within 24 min to reach a SoBi station. We set the threshold (what people are willing to travel). Gaussian says people are more willing to go 5 than 10, less willing to go 15 than 20. Progressively discount, but we dont know the willingness. If we had more information about how many people go 5, 10, etc. then using the Gaussian function would be possible. Otherwise, there are a lot of assumptions. Binary requires us to make fewer assumptions.

Disparity Analysis

An advantage of the use of adjusted weights for proportional allocation of demand and level of service it that, after rectifying the inflation artifact, they make it is possible to conduct accessibility disparity analysis in a very intuitive way.

For instance, an analyst interested in equity analysis could allocate the total level of service uniformly to every population unit. In other words, the total level of service (which equals the sum of accessibility over the system) can be divided by the number of population units in the system to return the Average Local Population Unit PPR. The resulting mean value, call it \(L_i^e\) then would be assigned to the population units as their equitable share of the total level of service in the system. Next, the equitable distribution of the level of service in each population unit is subtracted from the estimated accessibility to arrive at a disparity index. When the difference between these two quantities is positive, this would indicate that accessibility at that location exceeds its equitable share of level of service. On the other hand, when the difference is negative, accessibility at the location is below its equitable share of the level of service.

This approach is reminiscent of the Spatial Access Ratio (SPAR) proposed by Wan et al.[-@Wan2012SPAR], which is calculated as the ratio between a population centers accessibility and the mean accessibility across all population centers. Wan et al.[-@Wan2012] calculate SPAR based on the results of their 3SFCA method, by re-scaling the accessibility measures to reflect the percentage difference in each population centers accessibility relative to the mean. This measure is designed to overcome the sensitivity of existing FCA metrics to the impedance function. In contrast, the approach proposed here, enables more intuitive and interpretable results by preserving the system-wide population and level of service. In this way, a disparity index is useful to highlight the absolute difference in accessible provider-to-population ratios across population units.

The disparity for SoBi is shown in the following map. The figure reveals the spatial distribution in disparity, with levels of access that are lower than the mean in the periphery of the service area, compared to levels of access that are greater than the mean in the higher-density and more connected urban center. It is worth noting that levels of access that are greater than the mean are predominantly concentrated around the University in west Hamilton. Areas that have less than their equitable share of the level of service are some of the most socioeconomically disadvantaged areas in the city. Our analysis builds upon a previous and recent study [@hosfordWhoArePublic2018] which found that disadvantaged areas in Hamilton are better served by the SoBi system, compared to other Canadian cities [i.e., Toronto, Vancouver, Montreal, and Ottawa-Gatineau] where advantaged areas have greater access. The authors [@hosfordWhoArePublic2018] note Hamilton stands out in that the lower income neighborhoods are located near the city center and wealthier neighborhoods are in the surrounding suburban areas. Thus, relative to other Canadian programs, Hamiltons bicycle share program could more easily be established in lower income areas while still being near high population density areas. This is an artifact of the 2001 amalgamation of Hamilton with four surrounding communities. The urban core, which is Hamilton proper, remains predominantly disadvantaged compared to the 4 amalgamated and less densely populated areas (e.g., Dundas, Ancaster, Stoney Creek, Waterdown) that surround the city. Interestingly, Dundas is an advantaged area but also has lower accessibility that is less than their equitable share. However, by calculating the disparity index, we have shown that more advantaged areas within the SoBi service area have higher levels of service and exceed its equitable share of service.

Reaggregating accessibility

One advantage of the Balanced FCA approach is that accessibility can be reaggregated while preserving the population and level of service. Here, we reaggregate the population to DAs. This allows us to then join the DA-level accessibility to DA-level census data for further analysis.

Read the DA-level data:

load("hamilton_da_2016.RData")

Plot DAs:

ggplot(data = hamilton_da_2016) +
  geom_sf()

Project the Hamilton DA zones to the same projection of the SoBi Service Area:

hamilton_da_2016 <- st_transform(hamilton_da_2016, crs = st_crs(sobi_service))

Bounding box of DAs in serviced areas:

bounding_box <- st_bbox(sobi_service %>%
                          st_buffer(500))

Extract DAs in service area:

hamilton_da_sobi <- hamilton_da_2016[st_as_sfc(bounding_box),]

Plot accessibility and extracted DAs:

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = population_sobi_original,
          aes(color = accessibility_o)) +
  geom_sf(data = hamilton_da_sobi,
          fill = NA) + 
  scale_color_distiller(palette = "YlOrRd", 
                        direction = 1)

Spatial join:

accessibility_da_original <- population_sobi_original %>%
  st_join(hamilton_da_sobi %>% dplyr::select(DA))

Aggregate population and accessibility by DA:

accessibility_da_original <- accessibility_da_original %>%
  group_by(DA) %>%
  summarize(population = sum(population),

NOTE TO ELISE

You can get an API to use cancensus from CensusMapper. Once you have an API key, you can store it in your system this way:

set_api_key("your-key", install = TRUE)
